WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.140
So I am going to switch to, sometimes people say the stepsister, the stepsister that lets

00:00:06.140 --> 00:00:09.520
the sister have all the benefit and do all the work and stuff.

00:00:09.900 --> 00:00:11.880
But there's been a lot of work from the stepsister.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.600
So let's talk a little bit about it.

00:00:14.340 --> 00:00:20.160
So, you know, I think we're all very familiar with CD38 as a target.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:26.060
In fact, CD38 is the highest, you know, receptor on the surface of the plasma cell.

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:27.940
Hundreds of thousands of receptors.

00:00:28.060 --> 00:00:31.220
So it's a great target on the, you know, on the surface of the cell.

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:36.260
But it's also, you know, widely dispersed along the microenvironment.

00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:41.120
And so it's on Tregs, Bregs, other immunosuppressive, you know, cells, as we know.

00:00:41.220 --> 00:00:43.220
And so it works by two things.

00:00:43.340 --> 00:00:48.660
One, it works by directly targeting the cancer cell, but it also decreases the immunosuppressive

00:00:49.100 --> 00:00:50.180
microenvironment of the bone marrow.

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:57.340
Now, this, you know, back in the day, I don't know how many of you guys follow this, but

00:00:57.340 --> 00:00:58.040
back in the day, it was.

00:00:58.080 --> 00:00:59.000
It was a true race.

00:00:59.540 --> 00:01:02.720
It was Dara versus Issa, and it was a true race, and everybody presenting data.

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:06.620
And then all of a sudden, Issa got a flat tire, maybe two flat tires.

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:09.900
I actually think somebody knifed the tires, okay?

00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:12.560
And there we go.

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:20.060
So when we think about newly diagnosed myeloma, I'll just step back and say, our first decision,

00:01:20.500 --> 00:01:23.520
as Sergio told us earlier, is that are they a transplant candidate?

00:01:23.640 --> 00:01:24.280
Are they not?

00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:27.760
And if they're not a transplant candidate, are they frail and are they not?

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:28.040
And so.

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:29.540
I'm going to show some data about that.

00:01:29.980 --> 00:01:33.800
Now, I do like to say that myeloma is an art.

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:35.600
We paint various pictures.

00:01:35.900 --> 00:01:38.300
Everybody might like one of these different pictures better.

00:01:38.780 --> 00:01:39.560
I like them all.

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:40.740
I'd love to be in a museum.

00:01:41.240 --> 00:01:47.260
But that said, we can take all the drugs that we have and all these, you know, scenarios

00:01:47.260 --> 00:01:50.060
and put them together and we paint our own picture.

00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:55.200
What's the best induction for transplant eligible, transplant ineligible, the frail?

00:01:55.840 --> 00:01:57.480
Do we do treatment till forever?

00:01:57.740 --> 00:01:57.840
Is it?

00:01:57.840 --> 00:01:59.760
Do we use one, two, three, four drugs?

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:00.720
What do we do, right?

00:02:01.020 --> 00:02:02.600
Should MRD be used?

00:02:02.820 --> 00:02:08.800
These are questions that we still are answering, but it's becoming more and more a question

00:02:08.800 --> 00:02:12.220
of, yes, we start with a quad, right?

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:17.960
The first thing I want to show, one of my favorite ongoing studies, and that is basically

00:02:18.460 --> 00:02:20.660
the GMMG HD7 study.

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:27.060
This was one of the original studies to have MRD as an endpoint, and it was VRD versus

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:27.620
E-sub-VR.

00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:33.700
VRD as induction therapy, and the bottom left shows that actually by MRD negativity, the

00:02:33.700 --> 00:02:35.340
quad worked over the triplet.

00:02:35.860 --> 00:02:39.520
Harmut initially presented this in 2021 at ASH.

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:41.740
Here we are in 2026.

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:44.440
This regimen is not approved by the FDA.

00:02:45.020 --> 00:02:50.280
If MRD was accepted as an endpoint, this would have been approved five years ago.

00:02:50.640 --> 00:02:52.820
So that's how long it takes for some of these to develop.

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:56.780
But one thing I want to point out about this study is that we're going to have the four

00:02:56.780 --> 00:02:57.280
curves.

00:02:57.400 --> 00:03:00.500
I'm hoping to have the four curves at the end of this year.

00:03:00.780 --> 00:03:08.300
The four curves is no CD38 as induction or maintenance, CD38 only as induction, CD38

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:10.340
only as maintenance, or both.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:14.920
I actually think both is going to win, and I think ESA is going to lead the way on how

00:03:14.920 --> 00:03:16.120
to move this forward.

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:17.140
Okay.

00:03:17.860 --> 00:03:23.480
So other things that ESA has done, ESA has been compared or has been combined a lot with

00:03:23.480 --> 00:03:24.500
KRD, right?

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:27.180
ESA KRD is not a regimen, I think, a lot of it.

00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:27.980
A lot of us are using.

00:03:28.140 --> 00:03:33.500
But in fact, if you look at some of the studies, like the E-SKIA trial, you see a very high

00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:35.440
MRD negativity rate.

00:03:35.580 --> 00:03:41.300
And now with follow-up from ASCO and EHA, sustained MRD negativity rate, really high

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:43.400
rates of sustained, more than half of the patients.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.800
It also was used in the SKYLARC trial.

00:03:46.900 --> 00:03:49.660
The SKYLARC trial is probably Sergio's least favorite trial.

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:54.300
And this is a Boston trial, and this is a way to maybe say that you don't have to do

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:54.760
transplant.

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:56.960
But if you see in the bottom right, those people...

00:03:56.960 --> 00:04:01.040
Those people that have high-risk cytogenetic abnormalities, probably not going to transplant

00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:02.120
is not a good idea.

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:02.920
Right, Sergio?

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:04.060
All right.

00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:05.200
So you're still my mentor.

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:10.200
So the MITUS study, I'm not going to say much more of the MITUS study.

00:04:10.280 --> 00:04:14.400
The only thing I want to say about the MITUS, in the standard risk arms, the ones that got

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:17.120
MRD negativity, the maintenance is lenalidomide.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.820
In the high-risk, the ones that are MRD positive, the maintenance is actually ESA IBER, which

00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:23.440
is kind of cool.

00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:24.500
We'll see that.

00:04:25.020 --> 00:04:26.500
My favorite high-risk...

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:29.980
High-risk study is the GMG concept trial.

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:32.960
So Katja and Lisa put this forward.

00:04:33.220 --> 00:04:38.680
This is what I do, although often I do DARA because patients want a subcutaneous versus

00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:39.840
an IV.

00:04:40.300 --> 00:04:47.580
So it's four drug for the transplant-eligible induction, a transplant, four drug consolidation

00:04:47.580 --> 00:04:51.240
for four cycles, and then ESA KR forever.

00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:55.680
For me, it's two to three years until they actually have two to three years of MRD negativity.

00:04:55.880 --> 00:04:56.680
And they have...

00:04:56.960 --> 00:05:01.820
It's shown one of the best progression-free survival rates for high-risk.

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:06.940
This is high-risk multiple myeloma, both transplant-eligible on the left and transplant

00:05:06.940 --> 00:05:12.160
non-eligible on the right, showing PFS at five years of more than 50%.

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:13.380
That's a win.

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:16.420
That's a big win in my mind for high-risk multiple myeloma.

00:05:16.940 --> 00:05:17.140
All right.

00:05:17.260 --> 00:05:19.760
What about the transplant-ineligible?

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:24.280
There is a benefit, quote unquote, to the use of bortezomib.

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:26.440
We were all hoping there wouldn't be a benefit.

00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:26.800
Right.

00:05:26.800 --> 00:05:26.840
Right.

00:05:26.840 --> 00:05:26.920
Right.

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:26.940
Right.

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:31.200
So this is ESA RD versus ESA bortezomib RD.

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:34.660
And on the left, you see higher rates of MRD negativity.

00:05:34.960 --> 00:05:37.940
On the right, the progression-free survival, there just hasn't been enough follow-up.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.380
It probably will diverge over time.

00:05:41.700 --> 00:05:48.420
But the benefit, in my mind, of using this is weekly bortezomib for 12 cycles, and then

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:51.920
every other week for six more cycles, you can do it, and it's actually very effective.

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:56.920
There's also the EMRO study that looked at a quad in the...

00:05:56.920 --> 00:05:58.420
The transplant-ineligible.

00:05:58.940 --> 00:06:01.880
And the subset of this is the frail patient population.

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:08.420
Now, this is modified IMW frail score, looking based on age, modified Charleston comorbidity

00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:11.160
index in ECOG.

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:16.880
And you can see on the left, frail, on the right, non-frail, that the quad is better

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:17.580
than the triplet.

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:22.160
In my mind, quad really should be used for the majority of patients.

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:26.800
And I'll just say quality of life looks really good no matter...

00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:27.820
Which arm you're on.

00:06:29.020 --> 00:06:32.120
To Amrita's question, the on-body device.

00:06:32.300 --> 00:06:34.180
So this is an on-body device.

00:06:34.580 --> 00:06:38.000
Professor LeLue has actually presented this at multiple congresses.

00:06:38.300 --> 00:06:42.880
You put it on, you hit the button in the middle, and it administers the esotuximab over five

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:43.200
minutes.

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:45.860
Patients, some of the patients didn't want that.

00:06:45.960 --> 00:06:50.300
And so the nurse was allowed to give it like Dertumab to just give a, you know, basically

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:52.120
a five, three to five minute injection.

00:06:52.120 --> 00:06:56.760
But that said, equivalency rates between sub-Q and IV.

00:06:56.760 --> 00:06:58.520
Surprise, surprise, okay?

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:04.020
Now, in Europe, this actually has received a positive response from CHOMP.

00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:07.980
And so hopefully in the next, even the next couple months, this could be approved in Europe.

00:07:08.120 --> 00:07:12.120
In the US, they're looking at the package right now with the hope that we'll get access

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:14.260
to this this year in 2026.

00:07:14.880 --> 00:07:16.240
So that's in relapse refractory.

00:07:16.360 --> 00:07:17.680
But there is a GMG.

00:07:17.880 --> 00:07:25.340
One of my other favorite GMG studies is HD8, which is sub-Q versus IV and transplant eligible

00:07:25.340 --> 00:07:25.880
patients.

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:34.760
And on the right, GMG HD9, looking at esotuximab and ibertamide versus ibertamide as maintenance

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:35.220
therapy.

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:36.560
Pretty cool studies, actually.

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:37.920
Okay.

00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:41.880
And with that, I'll conclude that ESA, yes, it is the stepchild.

00:07:41.880 --> 00:07:47.680
It might actually be graduating to a better stepchild by the end of this year with sub-Q

00:07:47.680 --> 00:07:48.240
administration.

00:07:48.420 --> 00:07:49.140
Thank you for your attention.
